or Oct. 31. “We have however organised a refresher training for these same SPOs at the weekend,” Akinbiyi said. He said that another set of electoral officers would be trained towards improving the performance of personnel to be deployed for the elections. According to him, the three-day training held across the five Local Government Areas in the state – Lagos East Senatorial District-Somolu, Kosofe, Ikorodu, Ibeju-Lekki, and Epe – would be rounded-off on Wednesday. Akinbiyi said that the commission would be engaging National Youth Service Corps members in the elections. NAN recalls that INEC on Nov. 12 announced the rescheduling of the earlier postponed National and State Assembly bye-elections in 11 states for Dec. 5. The electoral body had shifted the bye-elections in Lagos, Bayelsa, Imo, and Cross Rivers indefinitely from Oct. 31 because of the violence that greeted the #EndSARS protests in some states. Candidates of 12 political parties will be contesting in the Lagos East Senatorial bye-elections. Eight candidates from various political parties will also contest in the Kosofe Constituency II, Lagos State House of Assembly bye-elections. Vanguard News Nigeria